How Glaciers Work

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Types of Glaciers

  • Continental Glaciers: Cover vast land areas (Antarctica, Greenland).
  • Alpine Glaciers: Found in mountainous regions.

Glacier Formation & Movement

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Glacier: A mass of ice that moves under its own weight.
  • Forms when accumulated snow compacts into firn, then glacial ice.
  • Equilibrium Line: The boundary between the zone of accumulation and the zone of ablation.
  • Glacial advance: More accumulation than melting.
  • Glacial retreat: More melting than accumulation.
  • Ice Flow Mechanisms:
    • Internal Flow: Ice deforms plastically under pressure.
    • Basal Sliding: If water is present at the base, ice slides over the bedrock.
    • Crevasses: Surface cracks due to differential movement.

Glacial Erosion

How Glaciers Erode

  • Glacial ice alone does not erode effectively; embedded rock fragments act like sandpaper.
  • Plucking: Ice pulls away chunks of bedrock.
  • Abrasion: Rock fragments scrape and polish surfaces.

Erosional Features

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Alpine Glacial Features
    • U-Shaped Valleys: Deep valleys with steep walls, carved by glaciers as they move.
    • ArÃªtes: Sharp ridges between glacial valleys.

    • Cirques: Bowl-shaped depressions where glaciers form.
    • Hanging Valleys: Tributary valleys left at higher elevations.
    • Truncated Spurs: Ridges cut off by glacier erosion.
  • Continental Glacial Features
    • Drumlins: Streamlined hills shaped by glaciers.
    • Roches MoutonÃ©es: Asymmetrical rock features smoothed by ice.

Alpine Glacial Features

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Factors Affecting Erosion

  • Ice thickness, slope, presence of rock fragments.

Glacial Deposition

How Glaciers Deposit Material

  • Till: Unsorted sediments deposited directly by glaciers.
    • Lodgement Till: Compacted beneath the glacier.
    • Ablation Till: Deposited from melting ice.
  • Glaciofluvial Deposits: Sorted sediments deposited by meltwater.
  • Glaciolacustrine Deposits: Sediments deposited in glacial lakes.
  • Glaciomarine Deposits: Sediments deposited in the ocean from icebergs.

Landforms Created by Glacial Deposition

  • Moraines: Ridges of till deposited at glacier edges.
  • Eskers: Sinuous ridges formed by subglacial rivers.
  • Kettles & Kettle Lakes: Depressions formed by melting ice blocks.
  • Outwash Plains (Sandurs): Extensive sediment deposits from glacial meltwater.

Depositional Features

  • Moraines: Ridges of till.
  • Drumlins: Streamlined hills from ice movement.
  • Kettle Lakes: Formed by melting ice blocks.

Glacial Lakes

  • Tarns: Cirque lakes.
  • Finger Lakes: Long, narrow lakes in glacial valleys.
  • Moraine Lakes: Formed behind moraines.
  • Kettle Lakes: Small depressions filled with meltwater.

Summary

  • Glaciation has shaped Earthâs landscape through erosion and deposition.
  • Glaciers are dynamic systems influenced by climate and topography.
  • Understanding glacial processes helps reconstruct past climates and landscapes.
